### LAYER 2: Job Posting Salary Scraping \'97 The Market Signal Layer\
\
**The strategic insight:** Jobstreet Indonesia lists salary ranges on a substantial fraction of its postings. Research published in *Jurnal Ketenagakerjaan* (Kemnaker's own journal, November 2025) confirmed Jobstreet as a primary source for labor market wage analysis \'97 and explicitly used scraped Jobstreet data for academic analysis.\
\
**Sources with public salary data:**\
| Platform | Salary Transparency | Indonesian Coverage | Scrape Difficulty |\
|---|---|---|---|\
| Jobstreet Indonesia | ~25-35% of postings show range | Very high (largest Indonesian job board) | Medium \'97 anti-bot measures but manageable |\
| Glints | ~30-40% of postings show range | High (tech/startup focus) | Low-Medium |\
| LinkedIn Indonesia | Partial (some postings, estimates) | Very high (professional) | High (aggressive bot blocking) |\
| Kalibrr | ~20-25% of postings | Medium (tech focus) | Low |\
| SIAPKerja Karirhub (Kemnaker) | Expanding \'97 as of 2026 companies are legally required to report salary ranges via Karirhub | Government-mandated coverage growing | Medium \'97 government API likely accessible |\
\
**The SIAPKerja insight (critical new development):**\
Permenaker No. 18/2024 explicitly mandates that all companies submit job vacancy data including wages and KBJI classification through the SIAPKerja Karirhub system. As of 2026, this reporting is legally required. This means Kemnaker is building a government-mandated salary database across all formal employers. If accessible via API, this is the most defensible data source in Indonesia \'97 government-mandated, regularly updated, comprehensive.\
\
**Scraping architecture (what to actually build):**\
\
```\
LAYER 2 AGENT PIPELINE:\
\
Agent 1: JobStreet Crawler\
- Runs every Monday 3am WIB (off-peak)\
- Targets: Top 100 job titles \'d7 5 cities (Jakarta, Surabaya, Bandung, Medan, Bali)\
- Extracts: title, salary_min, salary_max, company_size, industry, experience_level\
- Output: ~500-1,000 postings/week with salary data\
- Tool: Playwright headless browser + Supabase Edge Function\
- Legal: Jobstreet ToS permits non-commercial research; for commercial use \uc0\u8594  email Jobstreet\
  partnership team (they have data licensing program)\
\
Agent 2: Glints Crawler  \
- Same schedule as Agent 1\
- Targets: Same job titles, tech/startup focus\
- Output: ~200-400 postings/week with salary data\
\
Agent 3: SIAPKerja Monitor\
- Targets: Karirhub API (kemnaker.go.id/siapkerja)\
- Check for API documentation or submit formal data partnership request\
- Government data = safest legal footing\
\
Agent 4: Salary Normalizer\
- Input: Raw scraped salary ranges (e.g., "Rp 8 juta - 12 juta")\
- Normalizes: mid-point, P25 (= salary_min), P75 (= salary_max)\
- Deduplicates: same job title / same company / posted within 30 days\
- Flags: anomalies where salary_max > 3x salary_min (likely data error)\
- Output: Clean (job_title_normalized, city, p25, p50, p75, source, date)\
\
Agent 5: BPS Reconciliation Check\
- Weekly: Compare scrape-derived P50 vs. BPS-derived P50 for same job/city\
- Flag: If deviation > 40%, investigate data quality issue\
- Action: Down-weight scrape data for that job/city if flagging pattern persists\
```\
\
**Legal risk of scraping:** Medium. The hiQ Labs v. LinkedIn (US 9th Circuit, 2022) ruling established that scraping publicly accessible data is generally not a CFAA violation in the US. Indonesia has no equivalent precedent, but Indonesian IT law (UU ITE) focuses on unauthorized access to protected systems \'97 public-facing job listings without login required are generally accessible. Risk mitigation: robots.txt compliance, rate limiting, partnership email sent to each platform before scraping.\
